      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X |f_n - f| \\, d\\mu = 0 \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu = \\int_X f \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} (2g - |f_n - f|) \\, d\\mu \\le \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X (2g - |f_n - f|) \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The goal is to justify passing the limit under the integral. State the domination hypothesis, prove the limit is still integrable, then use Fatou on a nonnegative dominated error to force the integral error to vanish. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the Lebesgue theorem.</p><p>This is the Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem.</p>\n        <p>Let \\((X,\\mathcal A,\\mu)\\) be a measure space. Suppose \\((f_n)\\) is a sequence of measurable functions converging pointwise a.e. to \\(f\\), and there exists a non-negative integrable function \\(g \\in L^1(X, \\mu)\\) such that \\(|f_n| \\le g\\) a.e. for every \\(n \\ge 1\\). Then \\(f \\in L^1(X, \\mu)\\), \\(f_n \\in L^1(X, \\mu)\\) for all \\(n\\), and:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X |f_n - f| \\, d\\mu = 0 \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu = \\int_X f \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div></p>\n        <p><em>Proof:</em> Since \\(|f_n| \\le g\\) a.e. for all \\(n\\), passing to the limit pointwise a.e. yields \\(|f| \\le g\\) a.e. Since \\(g \\in L^1(X, \\mu)\\), we have \\(f \\in L^1(X, \\mu)\\) and \\(f_n \\in L^1(X, \\mu)\\).\n        We have \\(|f_n - f| \\le |f_n| + |f| \\le 2g\\) a.e., which implies \\(2g - |f_n - f| \\ge 0\\) a.e.\n        Applying Fatou's Lemma to the sequence of non-negative measurable functions \\((2g - |f_n - f|)\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} (2g - |f_n - f|) \\, d\\mu \\le \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X (2g - |f_n - f|) \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div>\n        Since \\(|f_n - f| \\to 0\\) a.e., the left-hand side is:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X 2g \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div>\n        For the right-hand side, since \\(g \\in L^1\\), we can pull the constant integral out of the limit inferior:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X (2g - |f_n - f|) \\, d\\mu = \\int_X 2g \\, d\\mu - \\limsup_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X |f_n - f| \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div>\n        Combining these yields:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X 2g \\, d\\mu \\le \\int_X 2g \\, d\\mu - \\limsup_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X |f_n - f| \\, d\\mu \\implies \\limsup_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X |f_n - f| \\, d\\mu \\le 0.\n        \\]</div>\n        Since the integral of a non-negative function is non-negative, we get \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X |f_n - f| \\, d\\mu = 0\\).\n        The convergence of the integrals follows because:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\left| \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu - \\int_X f \\, d\\mu \\right| \\le \\int_X |f_n - f| \\, d\\mu \\to 0.\n        \\]</div></p>"
