      "answerHtml": "<p>A dominating function \\(g \\in L^1(X, \\mu)\\) is typically found using one of the following mathematical strategies:\n        1. **Bounded Domains and Uniform Bounds:** If \\(\\mu(X) < \\infty\\) and there exists a constant \\(M > 0\\) such that \\(|f_n(x)| \\le M\\) a.e. for all \\(n \\ge 1\\), we choose \\(g(x) = M\\). Since \\(\\int_X M \\, d\\mu = M \\mu(X) < \\infty\\), \\(g\\) is integrable.\n        2. **Pointwise Supremum / Decay Estimates:** If the domain is unbounded (e.g., \\(\\mathbb{R}^d\\)), we seek an integrable function that bounds \\(|f_n(x)|\\) uniformly in \\(n\\).\n           - For example, if \\(|f_n(x)| \\le \\frac{C}{1 + |x|^{d+\\alpha}}\\) for some \\(\\alpha > 0\\), then \\(g(x) = \\frac{C}{1 + |x|^{d+\\alpha}}\\) is integrable on \\(\\mathbb{R}^d\\).\n           - If there is an integrable singularity, such as \\(|f_n(x)| \\le \\frac{C}{|x|^\\alpha}\\) for \\(\\alpha < d\\) on a bounded neighborhood of \\(0\\), we choose \\(g(x) = \\frac{C}{|x|^\\alpha}\\).\n        3. **Monotonicity:** If the sequence is bounded by a known integrable function \\(|f_n(x)| \\le h(x)\\) a.e. for all \\(n\\), then \\(g = h\\) is the dominating function.</p>"
