      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> Build the proof from below. Replace the sequence by the increasing envelopes \\(g_k=\\inf_{m\\ge k} f_m\\), apply Monotone Convergence to \\(g_k\\), and compare each \\(g_k\\) with the tail integrals. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove Fatou's Lemma.</p><p>Let \\((f_n)\\) be a sequence of non-negative measurable functions. Fatou's Lemma states:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} f_n \\, d\\mu \\le \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em>\n        1. For each \\(k \\ge 1\\), define the function \\(g_k(x) = \\inf_{m \\ge k} f_m(x)\\).\n        2. The sequence \\((g_k)\\) consists of non-negative measurable functions. Since the set of indices over which the infimum is taken shrinks as \\(k\\) increases, \\(g_k(x) \\le g_{k+1}(x)\\) for all \\(x \\in X\\). Thus, \\((g_k)\\) is pointwise monotonically increasing.\n        3. By definition, the pointwise limit is:\n           <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n           \\lim_{k\\to\\infty} g_k(x) = \\sup_{k\\ge 1} \\inf_{m \\ge k} f_m(x) = \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} f_n(x).\n           \\]</div>\n        4. For any \\(m \\ge k\\), we have \\(g_k(x) \\le f_m(x)\\) for all \\(x \\in X\\). By monotonicity of the integral:\n           <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n           \\int_X g_k \\, d\\mu \\le \\int_X f_m \\, d\\mu \\qquad \\forall m \\ge k.\n           \\]</div>\n        5. Taking the infimum over all \\(m \\ge k\\) on the right-hand side yields:\n           <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n           \\int_X g_k \\, d\\mu \\le \\inf_{m \\ge k} \\int_X f_m \\, d\\mu.\n           \\]</div>\n        6. Since \\((g_k)\\) is a monotonically increasing sequence of non-negative measurable functions converging pointwise to \\(\\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} f_n\\), the Monotone Convergence Theorem implies:\n           <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n           \\lim_{k\\to\\infty} \\int_X g_k \\, d\\mu = \\int_X \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} f_n \\, d\\mu.\n           \\]</div>\n        7. Taking the limit as \\(k \\to \\infty\\) on both sides of the inequality in Step 5:\n           <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n           \\int_X \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} f_n \\, d\\mu = \\lim_{k\\to\\infty} \\int_X g_k \\, d\\mu \\le \\lim_{k\\to\\infty} \\left( \\inf_{m \\ge k} \\int_X f_m \\, d\\mu \\right) = \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu.\n           \\]</div></p>"
