      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> One inequality is monotonicity of the integral. For the reverse one, approximate the limit from below by a simple function, use the sets where \\(f_n\\) eventually dominates it, and then let the approximation parameters go to the end. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the Monotone Convergence Theorem, or Beppo Levi Theorem.</p><p>Let \\((f_n)\\) be a sequence of non-negative measurable functions such that \\(f_n \\le f_{n+1}\\) pointwise a.e., and \\(f_n \\to f\\) pointwise a.e. The Monotone Convergence Theorem states:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X f \\, d\\mu = \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em> Since \\(f_n \\le f\\) a.e., monotonicity of the integral implies \\(\\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu \\le \\int_X f \\, d\\mu\\). Taking the limit gives:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu \\le \\int_X f \\, d\\mu.\n        \\]</div>\n        To prove the reverse inequality, let \\(s\\) be any non-negative simple function such that \\(0 \\le s \\le f\\) pointwise. Fix any \\(\\varepsilon \\in (0, 1)\\). For each \\(n \\ge 1\\), define the set:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        E_n = \\{ x \\in X : f_n(x) \\ge (1-\\varepsilon) s(x) \\}.\n        \\]</div>\n        1. Each \\(E_n\\) is measurable since \\(f_n\\) and \\(s\\) are measurable.\n        2. Since \\(f_n \\le f_{n+1}\\), the sets are nested: \\(E_n \\subset E_{n+1}\\).\n        3. We show \\(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty E_n = X\\) (up to a null set).\n           - If \\(f(x) = 0\\), then \\(s(x) = 0\\), so \\(f_n(x) \\ge 0 = (1-\\varepsilon)s(x)\\) holds for all \\(n\\), meaning \\(x \\in E_1\\).\n           - If \\(f(x) > 0\\), then \\((1-\\varepsilon)s(x) < f(x)\\). Since \\(f_n(x) \\to f(x)\\), there exists \\(N\\) such that \\(f_n(x) \\ge (1-\\varepsilon)s(x)\\) for all \\(n \\ge N\\), meaning \\(x \\in E_N\\).\n           Thus \\(E_n \\uparrow X\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\).\n        4. For any \\(n \\ge 1\\), we have \\(\\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu \\ge \\int_{E_n} f_n \\, d\\mu \\ge (1-\\varepsilon) \\int_{E_n} s \\, d\\mu\\).\n        5. Write the simple function \\(s\\) as \\(s = \\sum_{j=1}^m a_j \\chi_{A_j}\\), where \\(a_j \\ge 0\\) and \\(A_j\\) are disjoint measurable sets. Define the measure \\(\\nu(E) = \\int_E s \\, d\\mu = \\sum_{j=1}^m a_j \\mu(E \\cap A_j)\\). Since \\(\\nu\\) is a measure and \\(E_n \\uparrow X\\), continuity of measure from below implies:\n           <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n           \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_{E_n} s \\, d\\mu = \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\nu(E_n) = \\nu(X) = \\int_X s \\, d\\mu.\n           \\]</div>\n        6. Taking the limit inferior as \\(n \\to \\infty\\) on both sides of the inequality in Step 4 yields:\n           <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n           \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu \\ge (1-\\varepsilon) \\int_X s \\, d\\mu.\n           \\]</div>\n        7. Since this holds for any \\(\\varepsilon \\in (0, 1)\\), taking \\(\\varepsilon \\downarrow 0\\) yields \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu \\ge \\int_X s \\, d\\mu\\).\n        8. Taking the supremum over all non-negative simple functions \\(s \\le f\\) yields \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n \\, d\\mu \\ge \\int_X f \\, d\\mu\\).\n        Combining the two inequalities completes the proof.</p>"
