      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof should build a fast subsequence. Pick indices so the bad sets have summable measures, apply Borel-Cantelli, and conclude that outside one null set the errors eventually stay below a summable threshold. <em>Question focus:</em> Show that convergence in \\(L^1\\) implies convergence a.e. up to subsequences.</p><p>Let \\(f_n \\to f\\) in \\(L^1(X, \\mu)\\).\n        1. By Chebyshev's inequality, for any \\(\\varepsilon > 0\\), we have \\(\\mu(\\{|f_n - f| > \\varepsilon\\}) \\le \\frac{1}{\\varepsilon} \\|f_n - f\\|_{L^1} \\to 0\\). Thus, \\(f_n \\to f\\) in measure.\n        2. We extract a subsequence \\((f_{n_k})\\) such that for each \\(k \\ge 1\\), the set \\(A_k = \\{ x \\in X : |f_{n_k}(x) - f(x)| > 2^{-k} \\}\\) satisfies \\(\\mu(A_k) < 2^{-k}\\).\n        3. Since \\(\\sum_{k=1}^\\infty \\mu(A_k) < \\sum_{k=1}^\\infty 2^{-k} = 1 < \\infty\\), the First Borel-Cantelli Lemma implies that the set \\(E = \\limsup_{k\\to\\infty} A_k\\) of points belonging to infinitely many \\(A_k\\) has measure \\(\\mu(E) = 0\\).\n        4. For any \\(x \\notin E\\), there exists \\(K(x)\\) such that for all \\(k \\ge K(x)\\), we have \\(x \\notin A_k\\), which means \\(|f_{n_k}(x) - f(x)| \\le 2^{-k}\\).\n        5. Since \\(2^{-k} \\to 0\\), we have \\(\\lim_{k\\to\\infty} f_{n_k}(x) = f(x)\\) for all \\(x \\notin E\\), which proves \\(f_{n_k} \\to f\\) a.e.</p>"
