      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_a^b u(x) \\varphi'(x) \\, dx = - \\int_a^b v(x) \\varphi(x) \\, dx \\qquad \\forall \\varphi \\in C_c^1(a, b).\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\int_a^b u(x) \\varphi'(x) \\, dx = [u(x)\\varphi(x)]_a^b - \\int_a^b u'(x) \\varphi(x) \\, dx = - \\int_a^b v(x) \\varphi(x) \\, dx,\n          \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The problem is about translating between derivatives, integrals, and absolute continuity. Prove the easy direction by integrating the derivative, and the reverse direction by identifying the distributional derivative through test functions or integration by parts. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the characterization of absolutely continuous functions in terms of the integration by parts formula.</p><p>For \\(u \\in L^1(a, b)\\), \\(u\\) has an absolutely continuous representative on \\([a, b]\\) if and only if there exists \\(v \\in L^1(a, b)\\) such that:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_a^b u(x) \\varphi'(x) \\, dx = - \\int_a^b v(x) \\varphi(x) \\, dx \\qquad \\forall \\varphi \\in C_c^1(a, b).\n        \\]</div>\n        In this case, \\(v\\) is the weak derivative of \\(u\\).</p>\n        <p><em>Proof:</em>\n        - **Necessity:** Suppose \\(u\\) is absolutely continuous. By the Second FTOC, \\(u'\\) exists a.e. and \\(u' = v \\in L^1(a, b)\\). Integrating by parts for AC functions against \\(\\varphi \\in C_c^1(a, b)\\) yields:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\int_a^b u(x) \\varphi'(x) \\, dx = [u(x)\\varphi(x)]_a^b - \\int_a^b u'(x) \\varphi(x) \\, dx = - \\int_a^b v(x) \\varphi(x) \\, dx,\n          \\]</div>\n          since \\(\\varphi(a) = \\varphi(b) = 0\\).\n        - **Sufficiency:** Assume there exists \\(v \\in L^1(a, b)\\) satisfying the relation. Define the absolutely continuous function \\(w(x) = \\int_a^x v(t) \\, dt\\). By the necessity part, \\(w\\) satisfies \\(\\int_a^b w \\varphi' \\, dx = - \\int_a^b v \\varphi \\, dx\\). Subtracting the two equations gives:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\int_a^b (u(x) - w(x)) \\varphi'(x) \\, dx = 0 \\qquad \\forall \\varphi \\in C_c^1(a, b).\n          \\]</div>\n          We use the **Lemma:** If \\(h \\in L^1(a, b)\\) satisfies \\(\\int_a^b h \\varphi' \\, dx = 0\\) for all \\(\\varphi \\in C_c^1(a, b)\\), then \\(h\\) is constant a.e.\n          - *Proof of Lemma:* Fix \\(\\psi \\in C_c^\\infty(a, b)\\) with \\(\\int_a^b \\psi \\, dx = 1\\). For any \\(f \\in C_c^\\infty(a, b)\\), let \\(C_f = \\int_a^b f \\, dx\\). The function \\(\\eta = f - C_f \\psi \\in C_c^\\infty(a, b)\\) integrates to 0. Define \\(\\varphi(x) = \\int_a^x \\eta(t) \\, dt \\in C_c^1(a, b)\\). Since \\(\\varphi' = f - C_f \\psi\\):\n            <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n            0 = \\int_a^b h \\varphi' \\, dx = \\int_a^b h(x) (f(x) - C_f \\psi(x)) \\, dx = \\int_a^b \\left[ h(x) - \\left(\\int_a^b h(t)\\psi(t)\\,dt\\right) \\right] f(x) \\, dx.\n            \\]</div>\n            Since this holds for all \\(f \\in C_c^\\infty(a, b)\\), we have \\(h(x) = \\int_a^b h(t)\\psi(t)\\,dt = \\text{constant}\\) a.e.\n          Applying this Lemma to \\(h = u - w\\), we get \\(u(x) - w(x) = C\\) a.e., meaning \\(u(x) = C + \\int_a^x v(t) \\, dt\\) a.e., which is absolutely continuous.</p>"
