      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The problem is about translating between derivatives, integrals, and absolute continuity. Prove the easy direction by integrating the derivative, and the reverse direction by identifying the distributional derivative through test functions or integration by parts. <em>Question focus:</em> What is the relation between \\(W^{1,1}\\) and AC? Justify the answer.</p><p>In one dimension, the Sobolev space \\(W^{1, 1}(a, b)\\) is isomorphic to the space of absolutely continuous functions on \\([a, b]\\), up to equivalence classes of equality almost everywhere.\n        - **Justification:**\n          1. If \\(u \\in W^{1,1}(a, b)\\), its weak derivative \\(u'\\) is in \\(L^1(a, b)\\). By the sufficiency proof in Q23, \\(u\\) is equal a.e. to the absolutely continuous representative:\n             <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n             \\tilde{u}(x) = u(a) + \\int_a^x u'(t) \\, dt.\n             \\]</div>\n          2. Conversely, if \\(u\\) is absolutely continuous, then its classical derivative \\(u'\\) exists a.e., belongs to \\(L^1(a, b)\\), and by the necessity proof in Q23, acts as its weak derivative. Hence, \\(u \\in W^{1,1}(a, b)\\).</p>"
