      "keyStepsHtml": "",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof wants measurability reduced to preimages or level sets. Rewrite the target function using countable unions/intersections and known measurable building blocks, then use closure of the sigma-algebra. <em>Question focus:</em> Write the definitions of Borel measurable functions and Lebesgue measurable functions. Prove that continuous functions are both Borel and Lebesgue measurable.</p><p>Let \\(f : \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}\\) be a function.\n        1. **Borel Measurable:** \\(f\\) is Borel measurable if for every Borel set \\(B \\in \\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R})\\), the pullback \\(f^{-1}(B)\\) is a Borel set: \\(f^{-1}(B) \\in \\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R})\\).\n        2. **Lebesgue Measurable:** \\(f\\) is Lebesgue measurable if for every Borel set \\(B \\in \\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R})\\), the pullback \\(f^{-1}(B)\\) is a Lebesgue measurable set: \\(f^{-1}(B) \\in \\mathcal{L}(\\mathbb{R})\\).</p>\n        <p><strong>Proof for Continuous Functions:</strong> Let \\(f : \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}\\) be continuous.\n        Let \\(O \\subset \\mathbb{R}\\) be an open set. Since \\(f\\) is continuous, the inverse image \\(f^{-1}(O)\\) is open in \\(\\mathbb{R}\\).\n        Since every open set is a Borel set, \\(f^{-1}(O) \\in \\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R})\\).\n        The family of sets \\(S = \\{ A \\subset \\mathbb{R} : f^{-1}(A) \\in \\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R}) \\}\\) forms a \\(\\sigma\\)-algebra. Since \\(S\\) contains all open sets, it contains the \\(\\sigma\\)-algebra generated by open sets, which is \\(\\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R})\\). Thus, for every \\(B \\in \\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R})\\), \\(f^{-1}(B) \\in \\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R})\\), proving \\(f\\) is Borel measurable.\n        Furthermore, since \\(\\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R}) \\subset \\mathcal{L}(\\mathbb{R})\\), we also have \\(f^{-1}(B) \\in \\mathcal{L}(\\mathbb{R})\\) for all Borel sets \\(B\\), proving \\(f\\) is Lebesgue measurable.</p>"
