      "questionHtml": "State and prove the theorem about regularity of the Lebesgue measure.",
      "strategyHtml": "The proof is an approximation argument. State inner and outer regularity, prove it first for convenient measurable sets, then extend by monotone approximation and the definition of Lebesgue measure.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lambda(E) = \\inf \\{ \\lambda(O) : E \\subset O, \\, O \\text{ open} \\} \\quad (\\text{Outer Regularity})\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lambda(E) = \\sup \\{ \\lambda(K) : K \\subset E, \\, K \\text{ compact} \\} \\quad (\\text{Inner Regularity})\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof is an approximation argument. State inner and outer regularity, prove it first for convenient measurable sets, then extend by monotone approximation and the definition of Lebesgue measure. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the theorem about regularity of the Lebesgue measure.</p><p>Lebesgue measure \\(\\lambda\\) on \\(\\mathbb{R}^d\\) is regular: for any Lebesgue measurable set \\(E \\subset \\mathbb{R}^d\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lambda(E) = \\inf \\{ \\lambda(O) : E \\subset O, \\, O \\text{ open} \\} \\quad (\\text{Outer Regularity})\n        \\]</div>\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lambda(E) = \\sup \\{ \\lambda(K) : K \\subset E, \\, K \\text{ compact} \\} \\quad (\\text{Inner Regularity})\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em>\n        - **Outer Regularity:**\n          By definition of the Lebesgue outer measure, \\(\\lambda(E) = \\inf \\sum_{j=1}^\\infty |I_j|\\), where the infimum is taken over all countable coverings of \\(E\\) by open boxes \\(I_j\\).\n          For any \\(\\varepsilon > 0\\), choose a covering of \\(E\\) by open boxes \\(I_j\\) such that \\(\\sum_{j=1}^\\infty |I_j| < \\lambda(E) + \\varepsilon\\). Let \\(O = \\bigcup_{j=1}^\\infty I_j\\). Then \\(O\\) is an open set containing \\(E\\), and by subadditivity:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\lambda(O) \\le \\sum_{j=1}^\\infty \\lambda(I_j) = \\sum_{j=1}^\\infty |I_j| < \\lambda(E) + \\varepsilon.\n          \\]</div>\n          Taking the infimum over all open sets \\(O \\supset E\\) yields Outer Regularity.\n        - **Inner Regularity:**\n          - *Case 1: \\(E\\) is bounded.* Let \\(E\\) be contained in a bounded open box \\(U \\subset \\mathbb{R}^d\\).\n            Its complement in \\(U\\), \\(F = U \\setminus E\\), is also measurable. By Outer Regularity applied to \\(F\\), for any \\(\\varepsilon > 0\\), there exists an open set \\(O \\supset F\\) such that \\(\\lambda(O) < \\lambda(F) + \\varepsilon\\).\n            Let \\(K = U \\setminus O\\). Since \\(O\\) is open, \\(K\\) is closed, and since \\(K \\subset U\\), \\(K\\) is bounded, so \\(K\\) is compact.\n            Since \\(O \\supset U \\setminus E\\), we have \\(K = U \\setminus O \\subset E\\).\n            We have \\(\\lambda(U) = \\lambda(O) + \\lambda(K)\\) and \\(\\lambda(U) = \\lambda(E) + \\lambda(F)\\).\n            Therefore:\n            <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n            \\lambda(E) = \\lambda(U) - \\lambda(F) > \\lambda(U) - (\\lambda(O) - \\varepsilon) = \\lambda(K) + \\varepsilon.\n            \\]</div>\n            Thus \\(\\lambda(K) > \\lambda(E) - \\varepsilon\\), proving Inner Regularity for bounded sets.\n          - *Case 2: \\(E\\) is unbounded.* For each \\(R \\ge 1\\), define \\(E_R = E \\cap B_R(0)\\).\n            Since \\(E_R \\uparrow E\\), continuity of measure from below implies \\(\\lambda(E_R) \\to \\lambda(E)\\). For any \\(L < \\lambda(E)\\), choose \\(R\\) large enough such that \\(\\lambda(E_R) > L\\). Since \\(E_R\\) is bounded, Case 1 yields a compact set \\(K \\subset E_R \\subset E\\) such that \\(\\lambda(K) > L\\), proving Inner Regularity generally.</p>"
