      "questionHtml": "Prove the continuity of the measure along monotone sequences, either increasing or decreasing, under suitable further assumptions.",
      "strategyHtml": "The task asks for the two monotone-set limit rules. For increasing sets, decompose into disjoint increments; for decreasing sets, reduce to the increasing case by complements and use the finite-measure hypothesis.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n             \\mu(E) = \\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\mu(F_n) = \\lim_{N\\to\\infty} \\sum_{n=1}^N \\mu(F_n) = \\lim_{N\\to\\infty} \\mu(E_N).\n             \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n             \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\mu(E_1 \\setminus E_n) = \\mu(E_1 \\setminus E).\n             \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The task asks for the two monotone-set limit rules. For increasing sets, decompose into disjoint increments; for decreasing sets, reduce to the increasing case by complements and use the finite-measure hypothesis. <em>Question focus:</em> Prove the continuity of the measure along monotone sequences, either increasing or decreasing, under suitable further assumptions.</p><p>Let \\((X, \\mathcal{A}, \\mu)\\) be a measure space.\n        1. **Increasing Sequences:** If \\(E_n \\uparrow E = \\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty E_n\\), then \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\mu(E_n) = \\mu(E)\\).\n           - *Proof:* Define \\(F_1 = E_1\\), and \\(F_n = E_n \\setminus E_{n-1}\\) for all \\(n \\ge 2\\). The sets \\((F_n)\\) are pairwise disjoint and satisfy \\(\\bigcup_{n=1}^N F_n = E_N\\) and \\(\\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty F_n = E\\). By countable additivity:\n             <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n             \\mu(E) = \\sum_{n=1}^\\infty \\mu(F_n) = \\lim_{N\\to\\infty} \\sum_{n=1}^N \\mu(F_n) = \\lim_{N\\to\\infty} \\mu(E_N).\n             \\]</div>\n        2. **Decreasing Sequences:** If \\(E_n \\downarrow E = \\bigcap_{n=1}^\\infty E_n\\) and \\(\\mu(E_1) < \\infty\\), then \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\mu(E_n) = \\mu(E)\\).\n           - *Proof:* Define \\(A_n = E_1 \\setminus E_n\\). Since \\(E_n\\) is decreasing, \\(A_n\\) is increasing: \\(A_n \\uparrow \\bigcup (E_1 \\setminus E_n) = E_1 \\setminus E\\). Applying the increasing case yields:\n             <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n             \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\mu(E_1 \\setminus E_n) = \\mu(E_1 \\setminus E).\n             \\]</div>\n             Since \\(\\mu(E_1) < \\infty\\), we can write \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} (\\mu(E_1) - \\mu(E_n)) = \\mu(E_1) - \\mu(E) \\implies \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\mu(E_n) = \\mu(E)\\).\n        - **Counterexample for decreasing sequences without finite measure:** Let \\(X = \\mathbb{R}\\) with Lebesgue measure \\(\\lambda\\). Let \\(E_n = [n, \\infty)\\). We have \\(E_n \\downarrow \\varnothing\\), so \\(\\lambda(\\bigcap E_n) = 0\\). However, \\(\\lambda(E_n) = \\infty\\) for every \\(n \\ge 1\\). Thus, \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\lambda(E_n) = \\infty \\neq 0\\).</p>"
