      "answerHtml": "<p>For a metric space \\((X, d)\\), the Borel \\(\\sigma\\)-algebra \\(\\mathcal{B}(X)\\) is defined as the smallest \\(\\sigma\\)-algebra containing all open subsets of \\(X\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\mathcal{B}(X) = \\sigma(\\{ U \\subset X : U \\text{ is open} \\}).\n        \\]</div>\n        Classes of Borel sets include:\n        1. **Open Sets** and **Closed Sets**.\n        2. **\\(F_\\sigma\\) sets:** Countable unions of closed sets.\n        3. **\\(G_\\delta\\) sets:** Countable intersections of open sets.\n        4. **\\(F_{\\sigma\\delta}\\) sets** (countable intersections of \\(F_\\sigma\\) sets) and **\\(G_{\\delta\\sigma}\\) sets** (countable unions of \\(G_\\delta\\) sets).\n        \n        **Characterization on \\(\\mathbb{R}\\):** \\(\\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R})\\) can be generated by any of the following families of intervals (with endpoints in \\(\\mathbb{R}\\) or \\(\\mathbb{Q}\\)):\n        - Open intervals: \\(\\{(a, b) : a, b \\in \\mathbb{R}\\}\\).\n        - Closed intervals: \\(\\{[a, b] : a, b \\in \\mathbb{R}\\}\\).\n        - Half-open intervals: \\(\\{(a, b] : a, b \\in \\mathbb{R}\\}\\) or \\(\\{[a, b) : a, b \\in \\mathbb{R}\\}\\).\n        - Unbounded open intervals: \\(\\{(-\\infty, a) : a \\in \\mathbb{R}\\}\\) or \\(\\{(a, \\infty) : a \\in \\mathbb{R}\\}\\).\n        \n        **Characterization on \\(\\mathbb{R}^N\\):** \\(\\mathcal{B}(\\mathbb{R}^N)\\) is generated by open balls, by open rectangles of the form \\(\\prod_{j=1}^N (a_j, b_j)\\), or by rational rectangles.</p>"
