      "questionHtml": "State the Hahn-Banach theorem in the continuous extension form.",
      "strategyHtml": "",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        F(y) = f(y) \\qquad \\forall y \\in Y \\quad (\\text{i.e., } F|_Y = f),\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|F\\|_{X^*} = \\|f\\|_{Y^*}.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p>Let \\(X\\) be a normed space over the field \\(\\mathbb{K}\\) (where \\(\\mathbb{K} = \\mathbb{R}\\) or \\(\\mathbb{C}\\)), \\(Y\\) a linear subspace of \\(X\\), and \\(f \\in Y^*\\) a continuous linear functional on \\(Y\\). The continuous Hahn-Banach extension theorem states that there exists a continuous linear functional \\(F \\in X^*\\) such that:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        F(y) = f(y) \\qquad \\forall y \\in Y \\quad (\\text{i.e., } F|_Y = f),\n        \\]</div>\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|F\\|_{X^*} = \\|f\\|_{Y^*}.\n        \\]</div>\n        This guarantees that every continuous linear functional defined on a subspace can be extended to the entire space without increasing its operator norm.</p>"
