      "answerHtml": "<p>Let \\(X\\) be a real normed space. If \\(A, B \\subset X\\) are nonempty disjoint convex subsets of \\(X\\), and \\(A\\) is open, then there exist a continuous linear functional \\(L \\in X^*\\) with \\(L \\neq 0\\) and a real number \\(\\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R}\\) such that:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        L(a) < \\alpha \\le L(b) \\qquad \\forall a \\in A, \\, \\forall b \\in B.\n        \\]</div>\n        This means the disjoint convex sets are separated by the closed hyperplane \\(\\{x \\in X : L(x) = \\alpha\\}\\), with the open set \\(A\\) lying strictly on one side.</p>"
