      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>In \\(L^p(X, \\mu)\\) spaces:</strong>\n        - For \\(1 < p < \\infty\\), by the Riesz Representation Theorem, the dual of \\(L^p(X, \\mu)\\) is \\(L^q(X, \\mu)\\) where \\(\\frac{1}{p} + \\frac{1}{q} = 1\\). Thus, \\(f_n \\rightharpoonup f\\) weakly in \\(L^p(X, \\mu)\\) if:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n g \\, d\\mu = \\int_X fg \\, d\\mu \\qquad \\forall g \\in L^q(X, \\mu).\n          \\]</div>\n        - For \\(p = 1\\), on a \\(\\sigma\\)-finite measure space, the dual is \\(L^\\infty(X, \\mu)\\). Thus, \\(f_n \\rightharpoonup f\\) weakly in \\(L^1(X, \\mu)\\) if:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_n g \\, d\\mu = \\int_X fg \\, d\\mu \\qquad \\forall g \\in L^\\infty(X, \\mu).\n          \\]</div>\n        \n        <p><strong>In \\(\\ell^p\\) sequence spaces:</strong>\n        - For \\(1 \\le p < \\infty\\), weak convergence \\(x_n \\rightharpoonup x\\) means:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\sum_{k=1}^\\infty x_n(k) y(k) = \\sum_{k=1}^\\infty x(k) y(k) \\qquad \\forall y \\in \\ell^q,\n          \\]</div>\n          where \\(\\frac{1}{p} + \\frac{1}{q} = 1\\) (with \\(q = \\infty\\) when \\(p=1\\)).\n          A sequence \\((x_n)\\) converges weakly to \\(x\\) in \\(\\ell^p\\) if and only if it is norm-bounded and converges coordinatewise, i.e., \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} x_n(k) = x(k)\\) for each \\(k \\ge 1\\).</p>"
