      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> Use Polya backwards: weak convergence means testing against every continuous functional. So fix an arbitrary functional, estimate its value on the norm-convergent difference, and let the operator norm carry the limit to zero. <em>Question focus:</em> Show that strong convergence implies weak convergence.</p><p>Let \\((x_n)\\) be a sequence in a normed space \\(X\\) that converges strongly (in norm) to \\(x \\in X\\), meaning \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\|x_n - x\\|_X = 0\\). Let \\(L \\in X^*\\) be any continuous linear functional. By linearity and boundedness of \\(L\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |L(x_n) - L(x)| = |L(x_n - x)| \\le \\|L\\|_{X^*} \\|x_n - x\\|_X.\n        \\]</div>\n        Since \\(\\|L\\|_{X^*}\\) is finite and \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\|x_n - x\\|_X = 0\\), we have \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} |L(x_n) - L(x)| = 0\\). This holds for all \\(L \\in X^*\\), which proves that \\(x_n \\rightharpoonup x\\) weakly.</p>"
