      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The problem wants a sharp yes/no answer, not just a slogan. Decide the claimed implication, then either prove it from the definitions or choose a standard model example, verify the stated convergence/property, and explicitly show the missing conclusion fails. <em>Question focus:</em> Provide a counterexample for the converse implication.</p><p>Consider the Hilbert space \\(H = \\ell^2\\) and the sequence \\((e_n)_{n=1}^\\infty\\) of standard orthonormal basis vectors, where \\(e_n(k) = \\delta_{nk}\\).\n        By the Riesz Representation Theorem, any continuous linear functional \\(L \\in (\\ell^2)^*\\) is of the form \\(L(x) = \\langle x, y \\rangle\\) for some \\(y \\in \\ell^2\\). For this functional, we have:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        L(e_n) = \\langle e_n, y \\rangle = \\overline{y(n)}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Since \\(y \\in \\ell^2\\), we have \\(\\sum_{k=1}^\\infty |y(k)|^2 < \\infty\\), which implies \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} y(n) = 0\\). Thus, \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} L(e_n) = 0 = L(0)\\) for all \\(L \\in (\\ell^2)^*\\), proving \\(e_n \\rightharpoonup 0\\) weakly.\n        However, for all \\(n \\ge 1\\), we have \\(\\|e_n - 0\\|_2 = \\|e_n\\|_2 = 1\\). Since the norm of the difference does not converge to \\(0\\), the sequence \\((e_n)\\) does not converge strongly to \\(0\\).</p>"
