      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\sup_{n \\ge 1} |L(x_n)| < \\infty \\qquad \\forall L \\in X^*.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\sup_{n \\ge 1} \\|\\tau(x_n)\\|_{X^{**}} < \\infty.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The target is boundedness from pointwise bounded scalar tests. Translate the sequence into evaluation maps on the dual, apply Uniform Boundedness, then return through the canonical embedding to bound the original norms. <em>Question focus:</em> If \\(\\{x_n\\}\\) weakly converges to \\(x\\), can \\(\\{x_n\\}\\) be unbounded?</p><p>No, a weakly convergent sequence is always bounded.\n        Suppose \\(x_n \\rightharpoonup x\\) in a normed space \\(X\\). Then for every \\(L \\in X^*\\), the sequence of scalars \\((L(x_n))\\) is convergent, and hence bounded:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\sup_{n \\ge 1} |L(x_n)| < \\infty \\qquad \\forall L \\in X^*.\n        \\]</div>\n        Let \\(\\tau : X \\to X^{**}\\) be the canonical evaluation map, where \\(\\tau(x_n)(L) = L(x_n)\\). The dual space \\(X^*\\) is a Banach space. The family of linear operators \\(\\{\\tau(x_n)\\}_{n=1}^\\infty \\subset L(X^*, \\mathbb{K})\\) is pointwise bounded on \\(X^*\\). By the Uniform Boundedness Principle, this family is bounded in operator norm:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\sup_{n \\ge 1} \\|\\tau(x_n)\\|_{X^{**}} < \\infty.\n        \\]</div>\n        Since \\(\\tau\\) is an isometric embedding, \\(\\|\\tau(x_n)\\|_{X^{**}} = \\|x_n\\|_X\\) for all \\(n \\ge 1\\). Thus, \\(\\sup_{n \\ge 1} \\|x_n\\|_X < \\infty\\).</p>"
