      "questionHtml": "Show that if \\(x_n\\) weakly converges to \\(x\\) and \\(L_n\\) converges to \\(L\\) in \\(X^*\\), then \\(L_n(x_n)\\to L(x)\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\).",
      "strategyHtml": "The problem wants the proof strategy before the details. Identify the hypotheses, translate the desired conclusion into the right definition, choose the standard tool, and close by verifying the final limit, estimate, or identity.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |L_n(x_n) - L(x)| = |L_n(x_n) - L(x_n) + L(x_n) - L(x)| \\le |(L_n - L)(x_n)| + |L(x_n) - L(x)|\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\le \\|L_n - L\\|_{X^*} \\|x_n\\|_X + |L(x_n) - L(x)| \\le \\|L_n - L\\|_{X^*} M + |L(x_n) - L(x)|.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The problem wants the proof strategy before the details. Identify the hypotheses, translate the desired conclusion into the right definition, choose the standard tool, and close by verifying the final limit, estimate, or identity. <em>Question focus:</em> Show that if \\(x_n\\) weakly converges to \\(x\\) and \\(L_n\\) converges to \\(L\\) in \\(X^*\\), then \\(L_n(x_n)\\to L(x)\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\).</p><p>Let \\(x_n \\rightharpoonup x\\) in \\(X\\) and \\(L_n \\to L\\) strongly in \\(X^*\\).\n        Since \\((x_n)\\) is weakly convergent, it is norm-bounded, so there exists \\(M > 0\\) such that \\(\\|x_n\\|_X \\le M\\) for all \\(n \\ge 1\\).\n        We decompose the difference as:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |L_n(x_n) - L(x)| = |L_n(x_n) - L(x_n) + L(x_n) - L(x)| \\le |(L_n - L)(x_n)| + |L(x_n) - L(x)|\n        \\]</div>\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\le \\|L_n - L\\|_{X^*} \\|x_n\\|_X + |L(x_n) - L(x)| \\le \\|L_n - L\\|_{X^*} M + |L(x_n) - L(x)|.\n        \\]</div>\n        Since \\(L_n \\to L\\) strongly, \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\|L_n - L\\|_{X^*} M = 0\\).\n        Since \\(x_n \\rightharpoonup x\\), \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} |L(x_n) - L(x)| = 0\\).\n        Thus, \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} |L_n(x_n) - L(x)| = 0\\), which proves \\(L_n(x_n) \\to L(x)\\).</p>"
