      "strategyHtml": "The proof is compactness through the correct topology. Identify weak-star convergence as pointwise convergence on the predual, use Banach-Alaoglu or metrizability on bounded sets, and then translate compactness into a subsequence statement.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lim_{k\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_{n_k} g \\, d\\mu = \\int_X fg \\, d\\mu \\qquad \\forall g \\in L^1(X, \\mu).\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof is compactness through the correct topology. Identify weak-star convergence as pointwise convergence on the predual, use Banach-Alaoglu or metrizability on bounded sets, and then translate compactness into a subsequence statement. <em>Question focus:</em> Why can we say that from a bounded sequence in \\(L^\\infty\\) we can extract a subsequence which weakly* converges in \\(L^\\infty\\)?</p><p>The space \\(L^\\infty(X, \\mu)\\) on a separable, \\(\\sigma\\)-finite measure space is the dual space of \\(L^1(X, \\mu)\\), which is a separable Banach space.\n        According to the Banach-Alaoglu Theorem, the closed unit ball of the dual space \\((L^1)^*\\) is weak-star compact.\n        Furthermore, because the predual space \\(L^1(X, \\mu)\\) is separable, the weak-star topology restricted to any bounded ball of \\(L^\\infty(X, \\mu)\\) is metrizable.\n        Since compact metric spaces are sequentially compact, any bounded sequence \\((f_n)\\) in \\(L^\\infty(X, \\mu)\\) lies within a weak-star compact metric subspace. Thus, there exists a subsequence \\((f_{n_k})\\) and a function \\(f \\in L^\\infty(X, \\mu)\\) such that \\(f_{n_k} \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} f\\), which means:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lim_{k\\to\\infty} \\int_X f_{n_k} g \\, d\\mu = \\int_X fg \\, d\\mu \\qquad \\forall g \\in L^1(X, \\mu).\n        \\]</div></p>"
