      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\tau(x)(L_n) = \\tau(x)(L) \\implies \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} L_n(x) = L(x),\n          \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof is compactness through the correct topology. Identify weak-star convergence as pointwise convergence on the predual, use Banach-Alaoglu or metrizability on bounded sets, and then translate compactness into a subsequence statement. <em>Question focus:</em> Which is the relation between weak and weak* convergence? Justify your answer.</p><p>Let \\(X\\) be a normed space and \\(X^*\\) its dual. Weak convergence in \\(X^*\\) implies weak-star convergence. The converse holds if and only if \\(X\\) is reflexive.\n        - **Justification (Weak implies Weak-star):** Let \\((L_n)\\) be a sequence in \\(X^*\\) converging weakly to \\(L \\in X^*\\). This means that for every \\(\\Phi \\in X^{**}\\), \\(\\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\Phi(L_n) = \\Phi(L)\\). Let \\(\\tau : X \\to X^{**}\\) be the canonical evaluation map. For any \\(x \\in X\\), we have \\(\\tau(x) \\in X^{**}\\). Testing the weak convergence against \\(\\tau(x)\\) gives:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} \\tau(x)(L_n) = \\tau(x)(L) \\implies \\lim_{n\\to\\infty} L_n(x) = L(x),\n          \\]</div>\n          which is the definition of weak-star convergence \\(L_n \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} L\\).\n        - **Counterexample for the Converse (Non-reflexive case):** Let \\(X = c_0\\) (the space of real sequences converging to 0, with supremum norm). Its dual is \\(X^* = \\ell^1\\), and its bidual is \\(X^{**} = \\ell^\\infty\\). Let \\((e_n)_{n=1}^\\infty \\subset \\ell^1\\) be the standard basis. For any \\(x \\in c_0\\), \\(e_n(x) = x(n) \\to 0\\) as \\(n\\to\\infty\\). Thus \\(e_n \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} 0\\) weak-star in \\ell^1. However, to converge weakly to 0, it must satisfy \\(\\Phi(e_n) \\to 0\\) for all \\(\\Phi \\in \\ell^\\infty\\). Choosing \\(y = (1, 1, 1, \\dots) \\in \\ell^\\infty\\) defines a functional \\(\\Phi_y \\in X^{**}\\) such that \\(\\Phi_y(e_n) = y(n) = 1 \\not\\to 0\\). Thus \\((e_n)\\) does not converge weakly to 0.</p>"
