      "answerHtml": "<p>Let \\(X\\) be a normed space. Weak-star convergence in \\(X^*\\) satisfies:\n        1. **Uniqueness of Limits:** If \\(L_n \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} L\\) and \\(L_n \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} M\\), then \\(L = M\\) (since the predual \\(X\\) separates points of \\(X^*\\)).\n        2. **Boundedness:** If \\(X\\) is a Banach space, then any weak-star convergent sequence \\((L_n)\\) in \\(X^*\\) is norm-bounded: \\(\\sup_{n\\ge 1} \\|L_n\\|_{X^*} < \\infty\\) (by the Uniform Boundedness Principle).\n        3. **Lower Semicontinuity of the Norm:** If \\(L_n \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} L\\), then:\n           <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n           \\|L\\|_{X^*} \\le \\liminf_{n\\to\\infty} \\|L_n\\|_{X^*}.\n           \\]</div>\n           *Proof:* For any \\(x \\in X\\), \\(|L(x)| = \\lim |L_n(x)| = \\liminf |L_n(x)| \\le \\liminf (\\|L_n\\|_{X^*} \\|x\\|_X) = \\left(\\liminf \\|L_n\\|_{X^*}\\right) \\|x\\|_X\\). Taking the supremum over \\(\\|x\\|_X \\le 1\\) yields the result.\n        4. **Linearity:** If \\(L_n \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} L\\) and \\(M_n \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} M\\), then \\(\\alpha L_n + \\beta M_n \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} \\alpha L + \\beta M\\) for all scalars \\(\\alpha, \\beta\\).</p>"
