      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof is compactness through the correct topology. Identify weak-star convergence as pointwise convergence on the predual, use Banach-Alaoglu or metrizability on bounded sets, and then translate compactness into a subsequence statement. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the corollary of the Banach-Alaoglu theorem in a separable and reflexive Banach space.</p><p><strong>Corollary:</strong> Let \\(X\\) be a reflexive Banach space. Any bounded sequence \\((x_n) \\subset X\\) contains a weakly convergent subsequence \\((x_{n_k})\\).</p>\n        <p><em>Proof (Separable Reduction):</em> Let \\((x_n)\\) be a bounded sequence in \\(X\\) with \\(\\|x_n\\|_X \\le M\\) for all \\(n \\ge 1\\). Define \\(Y = \\overline{\\operatorname{span}}\\{x_n : n \\ge 1\\}\\). Since \\(Y\\) is a closed subspace of the reflexive space \\(X\\), \\(Y\\) is reflexive. Being the closure of the span of a countable set, \\(Y\\) is separable. Since \\(Y\\) is reflexive, the canonical map \\(\\tau : Y \\to Y^{**}\\) is an isometric isomorphism, meaning \\(Y^{**}\\) is also separable, which implies that the dual space \\(Y^*\\) is separable.\n        Consider the sequence of canonical images \\(\\tau(x_n) \\in Y^{**} = (Y^*)^*\\). Since \\(\\|\\tau(x_n)\\|_{Y^{**}} = \\|x_n\\|_Y \\le M\\), this is a bounded sequence in the dual of the separable space \\(Y^*\\). By the Banach-Alaoglu Theorem, the weak-star topology on the closed unit ball of \\(Y^{**}\\) is metrizable and compact, hence sequentially compact. Thus, there exists a subsequence \\(\\tau(x_{n_k})\\) and \\(\\Phi \\in Y^{**}\\) such that \\(\\tau(x_{n_k}) \\overset{*}{\\rightharpoonup} \\Phi\\) weak-star in \\(Y^{**}\\).\n        Since \\(Y\\) is reflexive, there exists \\(x \\in Y\\) such that \\(\\tau(x) = \\Phi\\). Evaluating the weak-star convergence on any \\(L \\in Y^*\\) yields:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\lim_{k\\to\\infty} L(x_{n_k}) = \\lim_{k\\to\\infty} \\tau(x_{n_k})(L) = \\tau(x)(L) = L(x).\n        \\]</div>\n        This proves \\(x_{n_k} \\rightharpoonup x\\) weakly in \\(Y\\). By the Hahn-Banach Theorem, every continuous functional on \\(X\\) restricts to a continuous functional on \\(Y\\), so \\(x_{n_k} \\rightharpoonup x\\) weakly in \\(X\\) as well.</p>"
