      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof should connect compactness with subsequences. Use boundedness to get weakly convergent subsequences when needed, apply compactness to get strong subsequences, and compare limits to identify the strong limit. <em>Question focus:</em> How is a compact operator related to operators of finite rank?</p><p>Every bounded linear operator of finite rank is compact. This is because the image of any bounded set \\(B \\subset X\\) is bounded in the finite-dimensional space \\(\\operatorname{Ran}(T)\\). By the Heine-Borel theorem, bounded subsets of finite-dimensional normed spaces are relatively compact.\n        The converse is false in infinite-dimensional spaces.\n        - **Counterexample:** Let \\(T : \\ell^2 \\to \\ell^2\\) be the diagonal operator defined by \\(T(x_n) = (x_n / n)\\). Its range is infinite-dimensional, so \\(T\\) is not of finite rank. We show \\(T\\) is compact by expressing it as the operator-norm limit of finite-rank operators \\(T_N\\) defined by \\(T_N(x) = (x_1, x_2/2, \\dots, x_N/N, 0, 0, \\dots)\\). The difference satisfies:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\|T - T_N\\|_{L(\\ell^2)} = \\sup_{\\|x\\|_2 \\le 1} \\left( \\sum_{k=N+1}^\\infty \\frac{|x_k|^2}{k^2} \\right)^{1/2} \\le \\frac{1}{N+1} \\to 0 \\quad \\text{as } N\\to\\infty.\n          \\]</div>\n          Since the space of compact operators is closed under the operator norm topology, the limit operator \\(T\\) is compact.</p>"
