      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          f \\in \\ker(I - T^*)^\\perp,\n          \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p>For linear equations of the form \\(u - Tu = f\\) on a Hilbert space \\(H\\) with \\(T\\) compact:\n        - If \\(\\ker(I - T) = \\{0\\}\\), the operator \\(I - T\\) is injective, and thus bijective with a bounded inverse. The equation has a unique solution \\(u = (I - T)^{-1}f\\) for any \\(f \\in H\\).\n        - If \\(\\ker(I - T) \\neq \\{0\\}\\), uniqueness fails, and the equation is solvable if and only if \\(f\\) satisfies the orthogonality condition:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          f \\in \\ker(I - T^*)^\\perp,\n          \\]</div>\n          which requires \\(\\langle f, v \\rangle = 0\\) for all solutions \\(v\\) of the homogeneous adjoint equation \\(v - T^*v = 0\\). If this condition is met, the solutions form a closed affine space of dimension equal to \\(\\operatorname{dim}(\\ker(I-T))\\).</p>"
