      "answerHtml": "<p>Let \\(T\\) be a compact operator on an infinite-dimensional Banach space \\(X\\).\n        1. **0 is in the spectrum:** We always have \\(0 \\in \\sigma(T)\\). (If \\(0 \\notin \\sigma(T)\\), then \\(T\\) is invertible, so \\(I = T \\circ T^{-1}\\) is compact, implying \\(X\\) is finite-dimensional, a contradiction).\n        2. **Non-zero spectrum consists of eigenvalues:** Every \\(\\lambda \\in \\sigma(T) \\setminus \\{0\\}\\) is an eigenvalue of \\(T\\) with finite-dimensional eigenspace \\(\\ker(\\lambda I - T)\\).\n        3. **Countability and accumulation:** The set \\(\\sigma(T)\\) is at most countable, and its only possible accumulation point is \\(0\\). Thus, the eigenvalues can be ordered as a sequence tending to \\(0\\).</p>"
