      "questionHtml": "State and prove the projection theorem and its corollary in Hilbert spaces.",
      "strategyHtml": "The argument is geometric. Minimize the distance to the closed convex set, use Hilbert-space parallelogram/convexity to get existence and uniqueness, then characterize the minimizer by an orthogonality inequality.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|x-p\\|_2 = \\inf_{y \\in K} \\|x-y\\|_2.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\operatorname{Re}\\langle x-p, y-p \\rangle \\le 0 \\qquad \\forall y \\in K.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The argument is geometric. Minimize the distance to the closed convex set, use Hilbert-space parallelogram/convexity to get existence and uniqueness, then characterize the minimizer by an orthogonality inequality. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the projection theorem and its corollary in Hilbert spaces.</p><p><strong>Projection Theorem:</strong> Let \\(K\\) be a nonempty closed convex subset of a Hilbert space \\(H\\). For every \\(x \\in H\\), there exists a unique \\(p \\in K\\) such that:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|x-p\\|_2 = \\inf_{y \\in K} \\|x-y\\|_2.\n        \\]</div>\n        The point \\(p\\) is characterized by the variational inequality:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\operatorname{Re}\\langle x-p, y-p \\rangle \\le 0 \\qquad \\forall y \\in K.\n        \\]</div>\n        - *Proof:* Let \\(d = \\inf_{y\\in K} \\|x-y\\|_2\\). Choose a sequence \\((y_n) \\subset K\\) such that \\(\\|x-y_n\\|_2 \\to d\\).\n          By the parallelogram identity applied to \\(u = x - y_n\\) and \\(v = x - y_m\\):\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          2\\|x-y_n\\|_2^2 + 2\\|x-y_m\\|_2^2 = 4\\left\\|x - \\frac{y_n + y_m}{2}\\right\\|_2^2 + \\|y_n - y_m\\|_2^2.\n          \\]</div>\n          Since \\(K\\) is convex, \\(\\frac{y_n + y_m}{2} \\in K\\), which implies \\(\\left\\|x - \\frac{y_n + y_m}{2}\\right\\|_2 \\ge d\\). Thus:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\|y_n - y_m\\|_2^2 \\le 2\\|x-y_n\\|_2^2 + 2\\|x-y_m\\|_2^2 - 4d^2 \\to 0 \\quad \\text{as } n, m \\to \\infty.\n          \\]</div>\n          Thus \\((y_n)\\) is Cauchy. Since \\(H\\) is complete and \\(K\\) is closed, \\(y_n \\to p \\in K\\). By continuity of the norm, \\(\\|x-p\\|_2 = d\\).\n          For uniqueness, if \\(p_1, p_2 \\in K\\) satisfy \\(\\|x-p_1\\|_2 = \\|x-p_2\\|_2 = d\\), the same inequality yields:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\|p_1 - p_2\\|_2^2 \\le 2d^2 + 2d^2 - 4\\left\\|x - \\frac{p_1 + p_2}{2}\\right\\|_2^2 \\le 0 \\implies p_1 = p_2.\n          \\]</div>\n          To prove the characterization, let \\(p \\in K\\) satisfy the variational inequality. For any \\(y \\in K\\):\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\|x-y\\|_2^2 = \\|(x-p) - (y-p)\\|_2^2 = \\|x-p\\|_2^2 + \\|y-p\\|_2^2 - 2 \\operatorname{Re}\\langle x-p, y-p \\rangle \\ge \\|x-p\\|_2^2.\n          \\]</div>\n          Conversely, if \\(p\\) is the projection and \\(y \\in K\\), then by convexity, \\((1-t)p + ty \\in K\\) for all \\(t \\in [0, 1]\\). Thus:\n          <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n          \\|x - p\\|_2^2 \\le \\|x - (p + t(y-p))\\|_2^2 = \\|x-p\\|_2^2 + t^2 \\|y-p\\|_2^2 - 2t \\operatorname{Re}\\langle x-p, y-p \\rangle.\n          \\]</div>\n          Dividing by \\(t > 0\\) and taking \\(t \\downarrow 0\\) yields \\(\\operatorname{Re}\\langle x-p, y-p \\rangle \\le 0\\).</p>\n        <p><strong>Corollary:</strong> If \\(M\\) is a closed linear subspace of \\(H\\), then \\(H = M \\oplus M^\\perp\\). Every \\(x \\in H\\) can be written uniquely as \\(x = m + z\\) with \\(m \\in M\\) and \\(z \\in M^\\perp\\).</p>\n        <p><em>Proof:</em> Since \\(M\\) is closed and convex, the projection \\(m = P_M(x) \\in M\\) exists. Let \\(z = x - m\\). By the variational characterization, for any \\(y \\in M\\) and any scalar \\(\\alpha \\in \\mathbb{K}\\), since \\(m + \\alpha y \\in M\\), we have \\(\\operatorname{Re}\\langle x - m, \\alpha y \\rangle \\le 0\\), which is \\(\\operatorname{Re}(\\overline{\\alpha}\\langle z, y \\rangle) \\le 0\\). Since \\(\\alpha\\) is arbitrary, we choose \\(\\alpha = \\langle z, y \\rangle\\) to obtain \\(|\\langle z, y \\rangle|^2 \\le 0 \\implies \\langle z, y \\rangle = 0\\) for all \\(y \\in M\\). Thus \\(z \\in M^\\perp\\).\n        For uniqueness, if \\(x = m_1 + z_1 = m_2 + z_2\\) with \\(m_i \\in M, z_i \\in M^\\perp\\), then \\(m_1 - m_2 = z_2 - z_1 \\in M \\cap M^\\perp = \\{0\\}\\). Thus \\(m_1 = m_2\\) and \\(z_1 = z_2\\).</p>"
