      "questionHtml": "Write and show the Holder inequality.",
      "strategyHtml": "Normalize first so the inequality becomes dimensionless. Prove the normalized estimate with Young inequality, then rescale; equality and zero cases should be handled before the normalization.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X |fg| \\, d\\mu \\le \\|f\\|_p \\|g\\|_q.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\frac{|f(x)g(x)|}{\\|f\\|_p \\|g\\|_q} \\le \\frac{|f(x)|^p}{p \\|f\\|_p^p} + \\frac{|g(x)|^q}{q \\|g\\|_q^q}.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> Normalize first so the inequality becomes dimensionless. Prove the normalized estimate with Young inequality, then rescale; equality and zero cases should be handled before the normalization. <em>Question focus:</em> Write and show the Holder inequality.</p><p><strong>Hölder's Inequality:</strong> Let \\(1 < p, q < \\infty\\) with \\(\\frac{1}{p} + \\frac{1}{q} = 1\\). If \\(f \\in L^p(X, \\mu)\\) and \\(g \\in L^q(X, \\mu)\\), then \\(fg \\in L^1(X, \\mu)\\) and:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X |fg| \\, d\\mu \\le \\|f\\|_p \\|g\\|_q.\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em> If \\(\\|f\\|_p = 0\\) or \\(\\|g\\|_q = 0\\), then \\(f = 0\\) a.e. or \\(g = 0\\) a.e. In this case, \\(fg = 0\\) a.e., so both sides of the inequality are \\(0\\), and the result holds.\n        Assume \\(\\|f\\|_p > 0\\) and \\(\\|g\\|_q > 0\\). For a.e. \\(x \\in X\\), apply Young's inequality pointwise to \\(a(x) = \\frac{|f(x)|}{\\|f\\|_p}\\) and \\(b(x) = \\frac{|g(x)|}{\\|g\\|_q}\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\frac{|f(x)g(x)|}{\\|f\\|_p \\|g\\|_q} \\le \\frac{|f(x)|^p}{p \\|f\\|_p^p} + \\frac{|g(x)|^q}{q \\|g\\|_q^q}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Integrating both sides over \\(X\\) yields:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X \\frac{|fg|}{\\|f\\|_p \\|g\\|_q} \\, d\\mu \\le \\frac{1}{p \\|f\\|_p^p} \\int_X |f|^p \\, d\\mu + \\frac{1}{q \\|g\\|_q^q} \\int_X |g|^q \\, d\\mu = \\frac{1}{p} + \\frac{1}{q} = 1.\n        \\]</div>\n        Multiplying by \\(\\|f\\|_p \\|g\\|_q\\) yields the inequality.</p>"
