      "questionHtml": "Write and show the Minkowski inequality.",
      "strategyHtml": "The proof is the triangle inequality for \\(L^p\\). Split \\(|f+g|^p\\), apply Holder to each term, cancel the common factor when nonzero, and treat the zero case separately.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f+g\\|_p \\le \\|f\\|_p + \\|g\\|_p.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |f+g|^p \\le (|f| + |g|) |f+g|^{p-1} = |f| |f+g|^{p-1} + |g| |f+g|^{p-1}.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof is the triangle inequality for \\(L^p\\). Split \\(|f+g|^p\\), apply Holder to each term, cancel the common factor when nonzero, and treat the zero case separately. <em>Question focus:</em> Write and show the Minkowski inequality.</p><p><strong>Minkowski's Inequality:</strong> For \\(1 \\le p \\le \\infty\\) and \\(f, g \\in L^p(X, \\mu)\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f+g\\|_p \\le \\|f\\|_p + \\|g\\|_p.\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em> If \\(p = 1\\), the triangle inequality on \\(\\mathbb{K}\\) yields \\(|f+g| \\le |f| + |g|\\). Integrating yields the result.\n        If \\(p = \\infty\\), since \\(|f| \\le \\|f\\|_\\infty\\) a.e. and \\(|g| \\le \\|g\\|_\\infty\\) a.e., we have \\(|f+g| \\le \\|f\\|_\\infty + \\|g\\|_\\infty\\) a.e., which yields \\(\\|f+g\\|_\\infty \\le \\|f\\|_\\infty + \\|g\\|_\\infty\\).\n        Now let \\(1 < p < \\infty\\), and let \\(q = \\frac{p}{p-1}\\) be the conjugate exponent. We have:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |f+g|^p \\le (|f| + |g|) |f+g|^{p-1} = |f| |f+g|^{p-1} + |g| |f+g|^{p-1}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Integrating both sides and applying Hölder's inequality to each term:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X |f+g|^p \\, d\\mu \\le \\|f\\|_p \\left( \\int_X |f+g|^{(p-1)q} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1/q} + \\|g\\|_p \\left( \\int_X |f+g|^{(p-1)q} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1/q}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Since \\((p-1)q = p\\), this simplifies to:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X |f+g|^p \\, d\\mu \\le (\\|f\\|_p + \\|g\\|_p) \\left(\\int_X |f+g|^p \\, d\\mu\\right)^{1/q}.\n        \\]</div>\n        If \\(\\|f+g\\|_p = 0\\), the inequality is trivial. If \\(\\|f+g\\|_p > 0\\), we divide both sides by \\(\\left(\\int_X |f+g|^p \\, d\\mu\\right)^{1/q}\\) (using \\(1 - 1/q = 1/p\\)) to obtain \\(\\|f+g\\|_p \\le \\|f\\|_p + \\|g\\|_p\\).</p>"
