      "strategyHtml": "Normalize first so the inequality becomes dimensionless. Prove the normalized estimate with Young inequality, then rescale; equality and zero cases should be handled before the normalization.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\frac{1}{p} + \\frac{1}{q} = 1.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        ab \\le \\frac{a^p}{p} + \\frac{b^q}{q}.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> Normalize first so the inequality becomes dimensionless. Prove the normalized estimate with Young inequality, then rescale; equality and zero cases should be handled before the normalization. <em>Question focus:</em> Write the definition of conjugate numbers. Show the Young inequality.</p><p>Conjugate exponents \\(p, q \\in (1, \\infty)\\) satisfy:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\frac{1}{p} + \\frac{1}{q} = 1.\n        \\]</div>\n        Young's inequality states that for all \\(a, b \\ge 0\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        ab \\le \\frac{a^p}{p} + \\frac{b^q}{q}.\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em> If \\(a = 0\\) or \\(b = 0\\), the inequality holds trivially.\n        Assume \\(a > 0\\) and \\(b > 0\\). Since the natural logarithm function \\(\\ln(x)\\) is strictly concave on \\((0, \\infty)\\), we have for \\(\\theta = 1/p \\in (0, 1)\\) and \\(u = a^p, v = b^q\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\ln(\\theta u + (1-\\theta)v) \\ge \\theta \\ln(u) + (1-\\theta)\\ln(v) \\implies \\ln\\left( \\frac{a^p}{p} + \\frac{b^q}{q} \\right) \\ge \\frac{1}{p} \\ln(a^p) + \\frac{1}{q} \\ln(b^q) = \\ln(ab).\n        \\]</div>\n        Since the exponential function is strictly increasing, applying it to both sides yields \\(ab \\le \\frac{a^p}{p} + \\frac{b^q}{q}\\).</p>"
