      "isProof": true,
      "bankRef": "Q2.20",
      "bankRefFull": "Theory Questions.pdf: Q2.20",
      "questionHtml": "Show the inclusion of \\(L^p\\) spaces. Which hypothesis is essential? Justify the answer.",
      "strategyHtml": "The proof depends on finite measure. Use Holder with the constant function \\(1\\) to compare norms, then show the hypothesis is essential by giving an infinite-measure counterexample.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f\\|_p \\le \\mu(X)^{1/p - 1/q} \\|f\\|_q.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X |f|^p \\cdot 1 \\, d\\mu \\le \\left( \\int_X (|f|^p)^{q/p} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{p/q} \\left( \\int_X 1^{\\frac{q}{q-p}} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1 - p/q} = \\|f\\|_q^p \\cdot \\mu(X)^{1 - p/q}.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof depends on finite measure. Use Holder with the constant function \\(1\\) to compare norms, then show the hypothesis is essential by giving an infinite-measure counterexample. <em>Question focus:</em> Show the inclusion of \\(L^p\\) spaces. Which hypothesis is essential? Justify the answer.</p><p><strong>Theorem:</strong> If \\(\\mu(X) < \\infty\\) and \\(1 \\le p \\le q \\le \\infty\\), then \\(L^q(X, \\mu) \\subset L^p(X, \\mu)\\), and:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f\\|_p \\le \\mu(X)^{1/p - 1/q} \\|f\\|_q.\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em> If \\(q = \\infty\\), then \\(|f(x)| \\le \\|f\\|_\\infty\\) a.e., which implies \\(\\|f\\|_p = \\left( \\int_X |f|^p \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1/p} \\le \\mu(X)^{1/p} \\|f\\|_\\infty\\).\n        If \\(q < \\infty\\), apply Hölder's inequality to the functions \\(|f|^p\\) and \\(1\\) with exponents \\(r = q/p \\ge 1\\) and conjugate exponent \\(s = \\frac{r}{r-1} = \\frac{q}{q-p}\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X |f|^p \\cdot 1 \\, d\\mu \\le \\left( \\int_X (|f|^p)^{q/p} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{p/q} \\left( \\int_X 1^{\\frac{q}{q-p}} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1 - p/q} = \\|f\\|_q^p \\cdot \\mu(X)^{1 - p/q}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Taking the \\(1/p\\)-th power of both sides yields \\(\\|f\\|_p \\le \\mu(X)^{1/p - 1/q} \\|f\\|_q\\).\n        The **finite-measure hypothesis** \\(\\mu(X) < \\infty\\) is essential. On infinite-measure spaces, there are no general inclusions. For example, on \\(X = (0, \\infty)\\) with Lebesgue measure, \\(f(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{x}} \\chi_{(0,1)}(x)\\) is in \\(L^1\\) but not in \\(L^2\\), while \\(g(x) = \\frac{1}{x} \\chi_{(1,\\infty)}(x)\\) is in \\(L^2\\) but not in \\(L^1\\).</p>"
