      "id": "functional-43",
      "subject": "functional",
      "chapter": "5. \\(L^p\\), \\(\\ell^p\\), And Core Inequalities",
      "priority": "★★",
      "isProof": true,
      "bankRef": "Q2.21",
      "bankRefFull": "Theory Questions.pdf: Q2.21",
      "questionHtml": "State and prove the interpolation inequality.",
      "strategyHtml": "Choose the exponent relation first, then factor \\(|f|^r\\) into two powers controlled by the endpoint norms. Apply Holder with the conjugate exponents determined by the interpolation parameter.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f\\|_r \\le \\|f\\|_p^\\theta \\|f\\|_q^{1-\\theta}.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X |f|^r \\, d\\mu \\le \\left( \\int_X |f|^{\\theta r u} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1/u} \\left( \\int_X |f|^{(1-\\theta)r v} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1/v} = \\left( \\int_X |f|^p \\, d\\mu \\right)^{\\frac{\\theta r}{p}} \\left( \\int_X |f|^q \\, d\\mu \\right)^{\\frac{(1-\\theta)r}{q}}.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> Choose the exponent relation first, then factor \\(|f|^r\\) into two powers controlled by the endpoint norms. Apply Holder with the conjugate exponents determined by the interpolation parameter. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the interpolation inequality.</p><p><strong>Interpolation Inequality:</strong> Let \\(1 \\le p < r < q \\le \\infty\\) and choose \\(\\theta \\in (0, 1)\\) such that \\(\\frac{1}{r} = \\frac{\\theta}{p} + \\frac{1-\\theta}{q}\\). If \\(f \\in L^p(X, \\mu) \\cap L^q(X, \\mu)\\), then \\(f \\in L^r(X, \\mu)\\) and:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f\\|_r \\le \\|f\\|_p^\\theta \\|f\\|_q^{1-\\theta}.\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em> First, assume \\(q < \\infty\\). The definition of \\(\\theta\\) yields \\(1 = \\frac{\\theta r}{p} + \\frac{(1-\\theta)r}{q}\\).\n        Write \\(|f|^r = |f|^{\\theta r} |f|^{(1-\\theta)r}\\). Apply Hölder's inequality to the product with conjugate exponents \\(u = \\frac{p}{\\theta r} > 1\\) and \\(v = \\frac{q}{(1-\\theta)r} > 1\\) (which satisfy \\(1/u + 1/v = 1\\)):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\int_X |f|^r \\, d\\mu \\le \\left( \\int_X |f|^{\\theta r u} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1/u} \\left( \\int_X |f|^{(1-\\theta)r v} \\, d\\mu \\right)^{1/v} = \\left( \\int_X |f|^p \\, d\\mu \\right)^{\\frac{\\theta r}{p}} \\left( \\int_X |f|^q \\, d\\mu \\right)^{\\frac{(1-\\theta)r}{q}}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Taking the \\(1/r\\)-th power yields \\(\\|f\\|_r \\le \\|f\\|_p^\\theta \\|f\\|_q^{1-\\theta}\\).\n        If \\(q = \\infty\\), we have \\(\\theta = p/r\\). Write \\(\\int_X |f|^r \\, d\\mu \\le \\|f\\|_\\infty^{r-p} \\int_X |f|^p \\, d\\mu = \\|f\\|_\\infty^{r-p} \\|f\\|_p^p\\). Taking the \\(1/r\\)-th power yields \\(\\|f\\|_r \\le \\|f\\|_p^{p/r} \\|f\\|_\\infty^{1 - p/r} = \\|f\\|_p^\\theta \\|f\\|_\\infty^{1-\\theta}\\).</p>"
