      "answerHtml": "<p>The sequence space \\(\\ell^p\\) is a special case of \\(L^p(X, \\mathcal{A}, \\mu)\\) where the underlying measure space is \\(X = \\mathbb{N}\\), \\(\\mathcal{A} = \\mathcal{P}(\\mathbb{N})\\) is the discrete \\(\\sigma\\)-algebra, and \\(\\mu = \\#\\) is the counting measure. A sequence \\(x = (x_k)_{k=1}^\\infty\\) is a function on \\(\\mathbb{N}\\), and its \\(L^p\\) integral is exactly the sum \\(\\sum_{k=1}^\\infty |x_k|^p\\).</p>"
