      "answerHtml": "<p>For sequence spaces, if \\(1 \\le p \\le q \\le \\infty\\), then \\(\\ell^p \\subset \\ell^q\\), and:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|x\\|_q \\le \\|x\\|_p.\n        \\]</div>\n        *Proof:* If \\(x = 0\\), the inequality is trivial. If \\(x \\neq 0\\), assume \\(\\|x\\|_p = 1\\) by scaling. Then \\(\\sum_{k=1}^\\infty |x_k|^p = 1\\), which implies \\(|x_k| \\le 1\\) for all \\(k \\ge 1\\). Since \\(q \\ge p\\), we have \\(|x_k|^q \\le |x_k|^p\\) for all \\(k\\).\n        Thus \\(\\sum_{k=1}^\\infty |x_k|^q \\le \\sum_{k=1}^\\infty |x_k|^p = 1\\). Taking the \\(1/q\\)-th power yields \\(\\|x\\|_q \\le 1 = \\|x\\|_p\\). By scaling, \\(\\|x\\|_q \\le \\|x\\|_p\\) holds generally.\n        This inclusion direction is opposite to that of \\(L^p\\) spaces on finite measure spaces because counting measure has infinite total mass, but its atoms have a positive lower bound (measure 1), forcing sequences to decay to 0 and thus remain bounded.</p>"
