      "bankRef": "Q2.23, Q2.24, Q2.25",
      "bankRefFull": "Theory Questions.pdf: Q2.23, Q2.24, Q2.25",
      "questionHtml": "For which \\(p\\) are \\(L^p(\\mathbb R)\\) and \\(\\ell^p\\) separable?",
      "strategyHtml": "",
      "keyStepsHtml": "",
      "answerHtml": "<p>Both \\(L^p(\\mathbb{R})\\) and \\(\\ell^p\\) are separable for \\(1 \\le p < \\infty\\).\n        - In \\(\\ell^p\\), the set of sequences with finite support and rational values is countable and dense.\n        - In \\(L^p(\\mathbb{R})\\), the set of simple functions of the form \\(\\sum_{j=1}^m q_j \\chi_{I_j}\\) where \\(q_j \\in \\mathbb{Q}\\) and \\(I_j\\) are intervals with rational endpoints is countable and dense.\n        The spaces \\(L^\\infty(\\mathbb{R})\\) and \\(\\ell^\\infty\\) are **not separable**.\n        - *Proof for \\(\\ell^\\infty\\):* For any subset \\(S \\subset \\mathbb{N}\\), let \\(\\chi_S \\in \\ell^\\infty\\) be its characteristic sequence. The set of all subsets \\(\\mathcal{P}(\\mathbb{N})\\) is uncountable, so there are uncountably many such sequences in \\(\\ell^\\infty\\). If \\(S_1 \\neq S_2\\), then \\(\\|\\chi_{S_1} - \\chi_{S_2}\\|_\\infty = 1\\).\n          Suppose for contradiction that \\(\\ell^\\infty\\) is separable, containing a countable dense subset \\(D\\). For each \\(S \\subset \\mathbb{N}\\), the open ball \\(B(\\chi_S, 1/3)\\) must contain an element of \\(D\\). Since these balls are pairwise disjoint, this defines an injection from the uncountable set \\(\\mathcal{P}(\\mathbb{N})\\) into the countable set \\(D\\), which is a contradiction.</p>"
