      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\tau(x)(L) = L(x) \\qquad \\forall L \\in X^*.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p>Let \\(X\\) be a normed space. The **canonical evaluation map** is the mapping \\(\\tau : X \\to X^{**}\\) defined by:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\tau(x)(L) = L(x) \\qquad \\forall L \\in X^*.\n        \\]</div>\n        <strong>Main Properties:</strong>\n        - \\(\\tau\\) is linear: \\(\\tau(\\alpha x + \\beta y)(L) = L(\\alpha x + \\beta y) = \\alpha L(x) + \\beta L(y) = \\alpha \\tau(x)(L) + \\beta \\tau(y)(L)\\).\n        - \\(\\tau\\) is an isometry: \\(\\|\\tau(x)\\|_{X^{**}} = \\|x\\|_X\\). Indeed, by definition, \\(\\|\\tau(x)\\|_{X^{**}} = \\sup_{\\|L\\|_{X^*} \\le 1} |L(x)|\\). By a corollary of the Hahn-Banach theorem, there exists \\(L \\in X^*\\) with \\(\\|L\\|_{X^*} = 1\\) and \\(L(x) = \\|x\\|_X\\). Thus, the supremum is exactly \\(\\|x\\|_X\\).\n        A Banach space \\(X\\) is **reflexive** if the canonical evaluation map \\(\\tau : X \\to X^{**}\\) is surjective (and thus is an isometric isomorphism between \\(X\\) and \\(X^{**}\\)).</p>"
