      "id": "functional-49",
      "subject": "functional",
      "chapter": "6. Low But Not Impossible Surprise Candidates",
      "priority": "★",
      "isProof": true,
      "bankRef": "Q2.31",
      "bankRefFull": "Theory Questions.pdf: Q2.31",
      "questionHtml": "State and prove the Banach-Steinhaus theorem, also called the Uniform Boundedness Principle.",
      "strategyHtml": "The proof uses Baire category to upgrade pointwise boundedness to uniform boundedness. Build closed sets where the operator family is bounded, find one with interior, then use linearity and scaling to get a global bound.",
      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\sup_{T \\in \\mathcal{F}} \\|Tx\\|_Y < \\infty \\qquad \\forall x \\in X,\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\sup_{T \\in \\mathcal{F}} \\|T\\|_{L(X,Y)} < \\infty.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The proof uses Baire category to upgrade pointwise boundedness to uniform boundedness. Build closed sets where the operator family is bounded, find one with interior, then use linearity and scaling to get a global bound. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the Banach-Steinhaus theorem, also called the Uniform Boundedness Principle.</p><p><strong>Uniform Boundedness Principle:</strong> Let \\(X\\) be a Banach space, \\(Y\\) a normed space, and \\(\\mathcal{F} \\subset L(X, Y)\\). If \\(\\mathcal{F}\\) is pointwise bounded, i.e.,\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\sup_{T \\in \\mathcal{F}} \\|Tx\\|_Y < \\infty \\qquad \\forall x \\in X,\n        \\]</div>\n        then \\(\\mathcal{F}\\) is uniformly bounded in operator norm:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\sup_{T \\in \\mathcal{F}} \\|T\\|_{L(X,Y)} < \\infty.\n        \\]</div>\n        <em>Proof:</em> For each \\(n \\ge 1\\), define the set \\(E_n = \\{ x \\in X : \\|Tx\\|_Y \\le n \\quad \\forall T \\in \\mathcal{F} \\} = \\bigcap_{T \\in \\mathcal{F}} \\{ x \\in X : \\|Tx\\|_Y \\le n \\}\\). Since each \\(T \\in \\mathcal{F}\\) is continuous, the set \\(\\{ x \\in X : \\|Tx\\|_Y \\le n \\}\\) is closed (preimage of the closed interval \\([0, n]\\)). Thus, \\(E_n\\) is closed.\n        By pointwise boundedness, for every \\(x \\in X\\), there is \\(n\\) such that \\(\\sup_{T\\in\\mathcal{F}} \\|Tx\\|_Y \\le n\\). Thus \\(X = \\bigcup_{n=1}^\\infty E_n\\).\n        Since \\(X\\) is complete, the Baire Category Theorem implies that at least one \\(E_N\\) must have non-empty interior. Thus, there exist \\(x_0 \\in X\\) and \\(r > 0\\) such that the closed ball \\(\\overline{B}(x_0, r) = \\{ x \\in X : \\|x-x_0\\|_X \\le r \\} \\subset E_N\\).\n        For any \\(T \\in \\mathcal{F}\\) and any \\(h \\in X\\) with \\(\\|h\\|_X \\le r\\), we have \\(x_0 + h \\in \\overline{B}(x_0, r) \\subset E_N\\). By linearity of \\(T\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|Th\\|_Y = \\|T(x_0+h) - Tx_0\\|_Y \\le \\|T(x_0+h)\\|_Y + \\|Tx_0\\|_Y \\le 2N.\n        \\]</div>\n        For any non-zero \\(x \\in X\\), letting \\(h = \\frac{r}{\\|x\\|_X} x\\), we have \\(\\|h\\|_X = r\\). Thus:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|T x\\|_Y = \\frac{\\|x\\|_X}{r} \\|Th\\|_Y \\le \\frac{2N}{r} \\|x\\|_X.\n        \\]</div>\n        This holds for all \\(x \\in X\\) and all \\(T \\in \\mathcal{F}\\), so \\(\\sup_{T \\in \\mathcal{F}} \\|T\\|_{L(X,Y)} \\le \\frac{2N}{r} < \\infty\\).</p>"
