      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        F(x) = \\langle x, y \\rangle \\qquad \\forall x \\in H.\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        u = x - \\frac{F(x)}{F(z_0)} z_0.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> Separate the zero functional from the nonzero case. For a nonzero functional, decompose the Hilbert space into kernel plus its orthogonal direction, choose the representing vector on that direction, and verify uniqueness by testing inner products. <em>Question focus:</em> State and prove the Riesz representation theorem in Hilbert spaces.</p><p><strong>Riesz Representation Theorem:</strong> Let \\(H\\) be a Hilbert space. For every continuous linear functional \\(F \\in H^*\\), there exists a unique \\(y \\in H\\) such that:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        F(x) = \\langle x, y \\rangle \\qquad \\forall x \\in H.\n        \\]</div>\n        Furthermore, we have the norm identity \\(\\|F\\|_{H^*} = \\|y\\|_H\\).</p>\n        <p><em>Proof:</em>\n        <strong>Uniqueness:</strong> Suppose there exist \\(y_1, y_2 \\in H\\) such that \\(F(x) = \\langle x, y_1 \\rangle = \\langle x, y_2 \\rangle\\) for all \\(x \\in H\\). Then \\(\\langle x, y_1 - y_2 \\rangle = 0\\) for all \\(x \\in H\\). Choosing \\(x = y_1 - y_2\\) yields \\(\\|y_1 - y_2\\|_H^2 = 0 \\implies y_1 = y_2\\).</p>\n        <p><strong>Existence:</strong> If \\(F = 0\\), we choose \\(y = 0\\).\n        Assume \\(F \\neq 0\\). Let \\(M = \\ker F = \\{x \\in H : F(x) = 0\\}\\). Since \\(F\\) is continuous and linear, \\(M\\) is a closed proper subspace of \\(H\\). By the Projection Theorem Corollary, \\(H = M \\oplus M^\\perp\\). Since \\(M\\) is a proper subspace, \\(M^\\perp \\neq \\{0\\}\\). Choose a non-zero vector \\(z_0 \\in M^\\perp\\).\n        Since \\(z_0 \\notin M\\), we have \\(F(z_0) \\neq 0\\). For any \\(x \\in H\\), define the vector:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        u = x - \\frac{F(x)}{F(z_0)} z_0.\n        \\]</div>\n        By linearity, \\(F(u) = F(x) - \\frac{F(x)}{F(z_0)} F(z_0) = 0\\), so \\(u \\in M\\). Since \\(z_0 \\in M^\\perp\\), \\(u\\) is orthogonal to \\(z_0\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        0 = \\langle u, z_0 \\rangle = \\left\\langle x - \\frac{F(x)}{F(z_0)} z_0, z_0 \\right\\rangle = \\langle x, z_0 \\rangle - \\frac{F(x)}{F(z_0)} \\|z_0\\|_H^2.\n        \\]</div>\n        Solving for \\(F(x)\\) gives:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        F(x) = \\left\\langle x, \\frac{\\overline{F(z_0)}}{\\|z_0\\|_H^2} z_0 \\right\\rangle.\n        \\]</div>\n        Thus, choosing \\(y = \\frac{\\overline{F(z_0)}}{\\|z_0\\|_H^2} z_0 \\in H\\) gives \\(F(x) = \\langle x, y \\rangle\\) for all \\(x \\in H\\).</p>\n        <p><strong>Norm Identity:</strong> If \\(y = 0\\), then \\(F = 0\\) and \\(\\|F\\|_{H^*} = 0 = \\|y\\|_H\\). If \\(y \\neq 0\\), then by Cauchy-Schwarz:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |F(x)| = |\\langle x, y \\rangle| \\le \\|x\\|_H \\|y\\|_H \\implies \\|F\\|_{H^*} = \\sup_{x \\neq 0} \\frac{|F(x)|}{\\|x\\|_H} \\le \\|y\\|_H.\n        \\]</div>\n        On the other hand, evaluating the functional at \\(x = y\\) gives:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |F(y)| = \\langle y, y \\rangle = \\|y\\|_H^2 \\implies \\|F\\|_{H^*} \\ge \\frac{|F(y)|}{\\|y\\|_H} = \\|y\\|_H.\n        \\]</div>\n        Combining these inequalities yields \\(\\|F\\|_{H^*} = \\|y\\|_H\\).</p>"
