      "keyStepsHtml": "<div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\mathbb{Q}[x] = \\bigcup_{n=0}^\\infty \\mathbb{Q}^{n+1},\n        \\]</div><div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f - P\\|_\\infty < \\frac{\\varepsilon}{2}.\n        \\]</div>",
      "answerHtml": "<p><strong>Proof sketch / Polya view:</strong> The task wants an explicit countable dense set. Define separability, then approximate continuous functions uniformly by polynomials and restrict to polynomials with rational coefficients. <em>Question focus:</em> Write the definition of separable metric space and show that \\(C^0([a,b])\\) is separable.</p><p>A metric space \\(X\\) is **separable** if it contains a countable, dense subset. That is, there exists a countable subset \\(D \\subset X\\) such that \\(\\overline{D} = X\\).</p>\n        <p>We show that the space \\(C^0([a, b])\\) of continuous, real-valued functions on the compact interval \\([a, b]\\), equipped with the supremum norm \\(\\|f\\|_\\infty = \\max_{x \\in [a, b]} |f(x)|\\), is separable by proving that the set of polynomials with rational coefficients, \\(\\mathbb{Q}[x]\\), is countable and dense in \\(C^0([a, b])\\).</p>\n        <p><strong>Countability:</strong> Every polynomial \\(P \\in \\mathbb{Q}[x]\\) can be written as \\(P(x) = \\sum_{k=0}^n q_k x^k\\) for some \\(n \\in \\mathbb{N}\\) and \\(q_k \\in \\mathbb{Q}\\). For each fixed \\(n\\), the set of polynomials of degree at most \\(n\\) with rational coefficients is in bijection with \\(\\mathbb{Q}^{n+1}\\). Since \\(\\mathbb{Q}\\) is countable, \\(\\mathbb{Q}^{n+1}\\) is countable for every \\(n\\). The set of all polynomials with rational coefficients is the countable union:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\mathbb{Q}[x] = \\bigcup_{n=0}^\\infty \\mathbb{Q}^{n+1},\n        \\]</div>\n        which is countable because a countable union of countable sets is countable.</p>\n        <p><strong>Density:</strong> Let \\(f \\in C^0([a, b])\\) and let \\(\\varepsilon > 0\\).\n        By the Weierstrass Approximation Theorem, there exists a polynomial \\(P(x) = \\sum_{k=0}^n c_k x^k\\) with real coefficients \\(c_k \\in \\mathbb{R}\\) such that:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f - P\\|_\\infty < \\frac{\\varepsilon}{2}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Let \\(M = \\max\\{|a|, |b|, 1\\}\\). Since \\(\\mathbb{Q}\\) is dense in \\(\\mathbb{R}\\), we can choose rational numbers \\(q_k \\in \\mathbb{Q}\\) for each \\(k = 0, 1, \\dots, n\\) such that:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |c_k - q_k| < \\frac{\\varepsilon}{2(n+1)M^n}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Define the rational polynomial \\(Q(x) = \\sum_{k=0}^n q_k x^k \\in \\mathbb{Q}[x]\\). For any \\(x \\in [a, b]\\):\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        |P(x) - Q(x)| = \\left| \\sum_{k=0}^n (c_k - q_k) x^k \\right| \\le \\sum_{k=0}^n |c_k - q_k| |x|^k \\le \\sum_{k=0}^n \\frac{\\varepsilon}{2(n+1)M^n} M^n = \\frac{\\varepsilon}{2}.\n        \\]</div>\n        Taking the supremum over \\(x \\in [a, b]\\) yields \\(\\|P - Q\\|_\\infty \\le \\frac{\\varepsilon}{2}\\).\n        By the triangle inequality:\n        <div class=\"formula\">\\[\n        \\|f - Q\\|_\\infty \\le \\|f - P\\|_\\infty + \\|P - Q\\|_\\infty < \\frac{\\varepsilon}{2} + \\frac{\\varepsilon}{2} = \\varepsilon.\n        \\]</div>\n        Since for any \\(f \\in C^0([a, b])\\) and any \\(\\varepsilon > 0\\), there exists \\(Q \\in \\mathbb{Q}[x]\\) with \\(\\|f - Q\\|_\\infty < \\varepsilon\\), the countable set \\(\\mathbb{Q}[x]\\) is dense in \\(C^0([a, b])\\). Hence, \\(C^0([a, b])\\) is separable.</p>"
